Cardio Good Fitness (Project 1)¶

Submitted by Sumant Sarkar (Jan'22 Cohort)¶

The goal of this project is to explore the cardio good fitness dataset and (a) come up with a customer profile (characteristics of a customer) of the different products (b) perform univariate and multivariate analyses (c) generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the company in targeting new customers

The dataset has the following attributes:

  1. Product - The model no. of the treadmill
  2. Age - Age of the customer in no of years
  3. Gender - Gender of the customer
  4. Education - Education of the customer in no. of years
  5. Marital Status - Marital status of the customer
  6. Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week
  7. Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit)
  8. Income - Income of the customer
  9. Miles- Miles that a customer expects to run

# Let's re-plot the income distribution, but with just three bins as opposed to the large number of bins we got in the pandas report.
# The bin boundaries are decided based on the min/max we saw earlier.

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
plt.hist(cdata["Income"], bins=[0,40000,80000,120000],edgecolor="yellow", color="blue")
ax.set_title('Income distribution')
plt.xlabel('Income ($)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
formatter0 = tkr.EngFormatter()
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter0)
ax.set_xticks([0,40000,80000,120000])
plt.show()



     


















    
    



























    

  1. Based on the pandas profile report above, we see that there are no missing values in any features.
    2. 

  2. TM195 sells twice as TM798 does.
    3. 

  3. The age distribution is right skewed. Most of the customers are around 25 years old. Mean age is 28 and median is 26 years.
    4. 

  4. There are significantly more male customers than female.
    5. 

  5. As to education level, most of the customers are college graduate (16 years) and some-college (~14 years) category.
    6. 

  6. A majority of the customers are partnered.
    7. 

  7. Usage has a right skewed distribution. So do income and miles.
    8. 

  8. The largest number of customers is the mid-income level customers. We will box plots later to get more insight into this.
    9.

# Univariate charts were created in the above report. Let's create a few more plots that have additional dimensions.
# One of the key goals of this project is to identify the customer profile of different products.
# So it makes sense to use the Product as a dimension in the plots. That's what we will do, to begin with.
# This box plot below shows the spread of Age for each of the Product in the dataset
sns.boxplot(data = cdata, x ='Product', y ='Age');



     


















    
    



























We notice that the median age across the products is almost identical. However, for TM798, the spread is much more narrow. Barring the outliers, it appears that this product is preferred by a narrow age band, whereas the other two products have an appeal for a larger age band. This should be looked into in a greater detail.

Customer profile¶
    

  1. The TM798 product is more prevalent among wealthier, more educated people who use the product more.
    2. 

  2. It also appears that this product appeals to customers in a narrow band of age (25 to 30 years old).
    3. 

  3. There seems to be no significant differences between the customer profiles of the other two products.
    4. 












Insights and recommendations¶
    

  1. The TM798 product sells the fewest in number. Clearly, this is not a high volume product. A high profit margin on this product will be a good idea. (Read below)
    2. 

  2. The TM798 product is associated with wealthier, more educated people who are getting more value from this product.
    3. 

  3. This customer segment can be expected to be willing to and capable of paying a higher price. A price increase can be tested for this product.
    4. 

  4. The 25-30 age bracket is a significantly large portion of the customer base. An upsell promotion campaign could be launched to switch customers to the (now higher priced) TM798 product, leading to a higher revenue and profit.
    5. 

  5. Since there is not a significant difference in the customer profile of the other two products, it could make sense to discontinue the one that has a lower profit margin. This could lead to savings in maintenance, sales training and spare part costs. Of course, this decision has to be made keeping in mind other factors that may prevent such a discontinuance.
    6.
